SIMPLE: seduce
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seduce
<hw>Se*duce"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Seduced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Seducing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>seducere</ets>, <ets>seductum</ets>; pref. <ets>se-</ets> aside +
<ets>ducere</ets> to lead. See <er>Duke</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
draw aside from the path of rectitude and duty in any manner; to entice
to evil; to lead astray; to tempt and lead to iniquity; to
corrupt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For me, the gold of France did not <qex>seduce</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically, to induce to engage in sexual
intercourse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To allure; entice; tempt; attract; mislead;
decoy; inveigle. See <er>Allure</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seducement</ent>⟦br⟧
